        <p>Most single dads don't need a lecture on saving money — they need a realistic system that works when life is already at full capacity. This is that system.</p>

        <div class="callout">
          <p><strong>The first move:</strong> before you optimize anything, know your actual numbers. One hour with your last three bank statements tells you more than any budgeting app.</p>
        </div>

        <h2>Know what you're actually spending</h2>
        <p>Most people guess wrong — usually low — on what they actually spend. Before you can fix anything, you need the real number. Pull three months of statements and sort every transaction into three buckets:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Fixed costs</strong> — rent/mortgage, car payment, insurance, phone, utilities. These are locked in for now.</li>
          <li><strong>Variable necessities</strong> — groceries, gas, kids' activities, clothing. Real costs, but you have some control.</li>
          <li><strong>Everything else</strong> — subscriptions, eating out, impulse buys. This is where the money usually hides.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Add it up. That number — compared to your take-home pay — tells you where you actually stand.</p>

        <h2>The emergency fund comes first</h2>
        <p>This sounds counterintuitive when money is tight, but an emergency fund isn't a luxury — it's what keeps a broken transmission from becoming a missed rent payment. Even $500 in a separate account breaks the cycle of crisis-to-crisis living.</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Start with a goal of $500–1,000 before anything else.</li>
          <li>Put it in a different account than your checking so it's not accidentally spent.</li>
          <li>Once you hit $1,000, your next goal is one month of fixed expenses.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>A framework that actually works on one income</h2>
        <p>The 50/30/20 rule is the standard advice. It doesn't work for a lot of single dads — 50% on needs alone is sometimes impossible. Here's an adjusted version:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Cover the non-negotiables first.</strong> Rent/mortgage, utilities, groceries, car, insurance, kids' school costs.</li>
          <li><strong>Set a hard weekly cash budget for variable spending.</strong> Groceries, gas, eating out — give yourself a number and stick to it.</li>
          <li><strong>Automate even a small amount to savings.</strong> $25 a paycheck is $650 a year. It adds up.</li>
          <li><strong>Cut subscriptions you forgot you had.</strong> Most people have $80–150/month in subscriptions they barely use.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where to cut without feeling it</h2>
        <p>Big categories, small pain:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Groceries:</strong> store brands for staples (pasta, canned goods, cooking oil) save 20–30% with no quality difference. Meal prep once a week cuts both food costs and decision fatigue.</li>
          <li><strong>Subscriptions:</strong> audit everything. Keep what you actually use weekly. Cancel the rest — you can always resubscribe.</li>
          <li><strong>Insurance:</strong> call your insurer once a year and ask if there's a better rate. Bundling home and auto typically saves $200–400/year.</li>
          <li><strong>Cell phone:</strong> prepaid carriers (Mint, Visible, Consumer Cellular) run on the same towers as the big carriers at 40–60% less.</li>
        </ul>

